I think there’s something worth exploring there.

Skimming is a movement along the surface of information. You’re minimizing depth to maximize coverage.

If you coined foiling by analogy to a hydrofoil or airfoil, the metaphor changes:

* A boat pushes through water.
* A hydrofoil uses the water to lift above it.
* Likewise, instead of pushing through every sentence, your mind uses just enough contact with the text to “lift” into the underlying structure.

So “foiling” could mean:

Reading for the latent shape rather than the literal sequence.

You’re asking:

* What’s the author’s operating model?
* What’s the invariant?
* What’s the pattern generating these paragraphs?
* If half the text disappeared, could I reconstruct it?

In Pantheon language, that’s reading the operators instead of the instances.

You can contrast several reading modes:

Mode	Goal
Scanning	Find a specific fact.
Skimming	Build a quick overview.
Close reading	Extract precise meaning.
Foiling	Ride the conceptual currents beneath the text.
Excavating	Reconstruct what the author didn’t explicitly say.
Cartography	Map relationships between ideas.
Inhabiting	Temporarily adopt the author’s worldview to see how it generates conclusions.

Foiling also has a second nice property: a foil becomes more efficient as speed increases. Below a certain speed, it drags; above it, it lifts.

That mirrors expertise. A novice has to read every sentence. An expert often reaches “takeoff speed” quickly because they recognize the conceptual currents and let them carry much of the load.

The metaphor isn’t perfect—unlike skimming, “foiling” isn’t an established reading term—but as a coined concept it has a coherent meaning. It captures a mode of reading where you’re trying to surface above the details without losing contact with them, using the structure of the ideas themselves to carry your understanding.